data.content:
Your code **doesn't use `Thread.Abort`** anywhere. It only uses `Thread.Start()`, `Thread.Join()`, and `Thread.Sleep()` — all of which work identically in .NET 8 and require **no migration**.

That said, for a .NET 8 modernization, consider replacing the manual thread management with `Parallel.ForEach` or `Task.WhenAll`:

```csharp
public class SimpleWorker
{
    public async Task RunBatchAsync(List<WorkItem> items)
    {
        await Parallel.ForEachAsync(items, async (item, ct) =>
        {
            await Task.Run(() => Process(item), ct);
        });
    }

    private void Process(WorkItem item)
    {
        item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
    }
}
```

This gives you better thread pool utilization and built-in cancellation support via `CancellationToken` — which *is* the modern replacement for `Thread.Abort` if you ever need to cancel work.
